<doc id="310921" wikidata="Q6543810" url="?curid=310921" title="Lie algebroid">
<text>In mathematics, a Lie algebroid is a vector bundle formula_1 together with a Lie bracket on its space of sections formula_2 and a vector bundle morphism formula_3, satisfying a Leibniz rule. A Lie algebroid can thus be thought of as a &quot;many-object generalisation&quot; of a Lie algebra.

Lie algebroids play a similar same role in the theory of Lie groupoids that Lie algebras play in the theory of Lie groups: reducing global problems to infinitesimal ones. Indeed, any Lie groupoid gives rise to a Lie algebroid, which is the vertical bundle of the source map restricted at the units. However, unlike Lie algebras, not every Lie algebroid arises from a Lie groupoid.

Lie algebroids were introduced in 1967 by Jean Pradines.

==Definition and basic concepts==
A Lie algebroid is a triple formula_4 consisting of

* a vector bundle formula_5 over a manifold formula_6
* a Lie bracket formula_7 on its space of sections formula_8
* a morphism of vector bundles formula_9, called the anchor, where formula_10 is the tangent bundle of formula_6

such that the anchor and the bracket satisfy the following Leibniz rule:

:formula_12

where formula_13. Here formula_14 is the image of formula_15 via the derivation formula_16, i.e. the Lie derivative of formula_15 along the vector field formula_16. The notation formula_19 denotes the (point-wise) product between the function formula_14 and the vector field formula_21.

One often writes &quot;formula_22&quot; when the bracket and the anchor are clear from the context; some authors denote Lie algebroids by &quot;formula_23&quot;, suggesting a &quot;limit&quot; of a Lie groupoids when the arrows denoting source and target become &quot;infinitesimally close&quot;.

=== First properties ===
It follows from the definition that

* for every formula_24, the kernel formula_25 is a Lie algebra, called the isotropy Lie algebra at formula_26
*the kernel formula_27 is a (not necessarily locally trivial) bundle of Lie algebras, called the isotropy Lie algebra bundle
* the image formula_28 is a singular distribution which is integrable, i.e. its admits maximal immersed submanifolds formula_29, called the orbits, satisfying formula_30 for every formula_31. Equivalently, orbits can be explicitly described as the sets of points which are joined by A-paths, i.e. pairs formula_32 of paths in formula_5 and in formula_6 such that formula_35 and formula_36
* the anchor map formula_37 descends to a map between sections formula_38 which is a Lie algebra morphism, i.e.
:formula_39

for all formula_40.

The property that formula_37 induces a Lie algebra morphism was taken as an axiom in the original definition of Lie algebroid. Such redundancy, despite being known from an algebraic point of view already before Pradine&#x27;s definition, was noticed only much later.

=== Subalgebroids and ideals ===
A Lie subalgebroid of a Lie algebroid formula_4 is a vector subbundle formula_43 of the restriction formula_44 such that formula_45 takes values in formula_46 and formula_47 is a Lie subalgebra of formula_2. Clearly, formula_43 admits a unique Lie algebroid structure such that formula_50 is a Lie algebra morphism. With the language introduced below, the inclusion formula_51 is a Lie algebroid morphism.

A Lie subalgebroid is called wide if formula_52. In analogy to the standard definition for Lie algebra, an ideal of a Lie algebroid is wide Lie subalgebroid formula_53 such that formula_54 is a Lie ideal. Such notion proved to be very restrictive, since formula_55 is forced to be inside the isotropy bundle formula_56. For this reason, the more flexible notion of infinitesimal ideal system has been introduced.

=== Morphisms ===
A Lie algebroid morphism between two Lie algebroids formula_57 and formula_58 with the same base formula_6 is a vector bundle morphism formula_60 which is compatible with the Lie brackets, i.e. formula_61 for every formula_62, and with the anchors, i.e. formula_63.

A similar notion can be formulated for morphisms with different bases, but the compatibility with the Lie brackets becomes more involved. Equivalently, one can ask that the graph of formula_60 to be a subalgebroid of the direct product formula_65 (introduced below).

Lie algebroids together with their morphisms form a category.

== Examples ==

=== Trivial and extreme cases ===
* Given any manifold formula_6, its tangent Lie algebroid is the tangent bundle formula_67 together with the Lie bracket of vector fields and the identity of formula_10 as an anchor.
*Given any manifold formula_6, the zero vector bundle formula_70 is a Lie algebroid with zero bracket and anchor.
*Lie algebroids formula_71 over a point are the same thing as Lie algebras.
* More generally, any bundles of Lie algebras is Lie algebroid with zero anchor and Lie bracket defined pointwise.

=== Examples from differential geometry ===
* Given a foliation formula_72 on formula_6, its foliation algebroid is the associated involutive subbundle formula_74, with brackets and anchor induced from the tangent Lie algebroid.
* Given the action of a Lie algebra &quot;formula_75&quot; on a manifold formula_6, its action algebroid is the trivial vector bundle formula_77, with anchor given by the Lie algebra action and brackets uniquely determined by the bracket of formula_75 on constant sections formula_79 and by the Leibniz identity.
*Given a principal &quot;G&quot;-bundle &quot;formula_80&quot; over a manifold &quot;formula_6&quot;, its Atiyah algebroid is the Lie algebroid formula_82 fitting in the following short exact sequence:
*:formula_83
: The space of sections of the Atiyah algebroid is the Lie algebra of &quot;formula_84&quot;-invariant vector fields on &quot;formula_80&quot;, its isotropy Lie algebra bundle is isomorphic to the adjoint vector bundle formula_86, and the right splittings of the sequence above are principal connections on &quot;formula_80.&quot;
*Given a vector bundle formula_88, its general linear algebroid, denoted by &quot;formula_89&quot; or &quot;formula_90&quot;, is the vector bundle whose sections are derivations of formula_91, i.e. first-order differential operators formula_92 admitting a vector field formula_93 such that formula_94 for every formula_95. The anchor is simply the assignment formula_96 and the Lie bracket is given by the commutator of differential operators.
*Given a Poisson manifold &quot;formula_97&quot;, its cotangent algebroid is the cotangent vector bundle &quot;formula_98&quot;, with Lie bracket &quot;formula_99&quot; and anchor map &quot;formula_100&quot;.
*Given a closed 2-form formula_101, the vector bundle &quot;formula_102&quot; is a Lie algebroid with anchor the projection on the first component and Lie bracket&quot;formula_103&quot;Actually, the bracket above can be defined for any 2-form formula_104, but formula_105 is a Lie algebroid if and only if formula_104 is closed.

=== Constructions from other Lie algebroids ===

* Given any Lie algebroid formula_107, there is a Lie algebroid formula_108, called its tangent algebroid, obtained by considering the tangent bundle of formula_5 and formula_6 and the differential of the anchor.
* Given any Lie algebroid formula_111, there is a Lie algebroid formula_112, called its k-jet algebroid, obtained by considering the k-jet bundle of formula_22, with Lie bracket uniquely defined by formula_114 and anchor formula_115.
*Given two Lie algebroids formula_116 and formula_117, their direct product is the unique Lie algebroid formula_118 with anchor formula_119 and such that formula_120 is a Lie algebra morphism.
*Given a Lie algebroid formula_111 and a map formula_122 whose differential is transverse to the anchor map formula_123 (for instance, it is enough for formula_15 to be a surjective submersion), the pullback algebroid is the unique Lie algebroid formula_125, with formula_126 the pullback vector bundle, and formula_127 the projection on the first component, such that formula_128 is a Lie algebroid morphism.

== Important classes of Lie algebroids ==

=== Totally intransitive Lie algebroids ===
A Lie algebroid is called totally intransitive if the anchor map formula_123 is zero.

Bundle of Lie algebras (hence also Lie algebras) are totally intransitive. This actually exhaust completely the list of totally intransitive Lie algebroids: indeed, if formula_5 is totally intransitive, it must coincide with its isotropy Lie algebra bundle.

=== Transitive Lie algebroids ===
A Lie algebroid is called transitive if the anchor map formula_123 is surjective. As a consequence:

* there is a short exact sequenceformula_132
* right-splitting of formula_37 defines a principal bundle connections on formula_56;
* the isotropy bundle formula_56 is locally trivial (as bundle of Lie algebras);
* the pullback of formula_5 exist for every formula_122.

The prototypical examples of transitive Lie algebroids are Atiyah algebroids. For instance:

* tangent algebroids formula_10 are trivially transitive (indeed, they are Atiyah algebroid of the principal formula_139-bundle formula_140)
* Lie algebras formula_75 are trivially transitive (indeed, they are Atiyah algebroid of the principal formula_84-bundle formula_143, for formula_84 an integration of formula_75)
* general linear algebroids formula_89 are transitive (indeed, they are Atiyah algebroids of the frame bundle formula_147)

In analogy to Atiyah algebroids, an arbitrary transitive Lie algebroid is also called abstract Atiyah sequence, and its isotropy algebra bundle formula_56 is also called adjoint bundle. However, it is important to stress that not every transitive Lie algebroid is an Atiyah algebroid. For instance:

* pullbacks of transitive algebroids are transitive
* cotangent algebroids formula_149 associated to Poisson manifolds &quot;formula_97&quot; are transitive if and only if the Poisson structure &quot;formula_151&quot; is non-degenerate
* Lie algebroids formula_105 defined by closed 2-forms are transitive

These examples are very relevant in the theory of integration of Lie algebroid (see below): while any Atiyah algebroid is integrable (to a gauge groupoid), not every transitive Lie algebroid is integrable.

=== Regular Lie algebroids ===
A Lie algebroid is called regular if the anchor map formula_123 is of constant rank. As a consequence

* the image of formula_37 defines a regular foliation on formula_6;
* the restriction of formula_5 over each leaf formula_157 is a transitive Lie algebroid.

For instance:

* any transitive Lie algebroid is regular (the anchor has maximal rank);
* any totally intransitive Lie algebroids is regular (the anchor has zero rank);
* foliation algebroids are always regular;
* cotangent algebroids formula_149 associated to Poisson manifolds &quot;formula_97&quot; are regular if and only if the Poisson structure &quot;formula_151&quot; is regular.

== Further related concepts ==

=== Actions ===
An action of a Lie algebroid &quot;formula_22&quot; on a manifold P along a smooth map &quot;formula_162&quot; consists of a Lie algebra morphismformula_163such that, for every &quot;formula_164&quot;,formula_165Of course, when &quot;formula_166&quot;, both the anchor &quot;formula_71&quot; and the map &quot;formula_168&quot; must be trivial, therefore both conditions are empty, and we recover the standard notion of action of a Lie algebra on a manifold.

=== Connections ===
Given a Lie algebroid &quot;formula_22&quot;, an A-connection on a vector bundle &quot;formula_88&quot; consists of an &quot;formula_171&quot;-bilinear mapformula_172which is &quot;formula_173&quot;-linear in the first factor and satisfies the following Leibniz rule:formula_174for every &quot;formula_175&quot;, where &quot;formula_176&quot; denotes the Lie derivative with respect to the vector field &quot;formula_177.&quot;

The curvature of an A-connection &quot;formula_178&quot; is the &quot;formula_173&quot;-bilinear mapformula_180and &quot;formula_178&quot; is called flat if &quot;formula_182.&quot;

Of course, when &quot;formula_183&quot;, we recover the standard notion of connection on a vector bundle, as well as those of curvature and flatness.

=== Representations ===
A representation of a Lie algebroid &quot;formula_22&quot; is a vector bundle &quot;formula_88&quot; together with a flat A-connection &quot;formula_178&quot;. Equivalently, a representation &quot;formula_187&quot; is a Lie algebroid morphism &quot;formula_188&quot;.

The set &quot;formula_189&quot; of isomorphism classes of representations of a Lie algebroid &quot;formula_22&quot; has a natural structure of semiring, with direct sums and tensor products of vector bundles.

Examples include the following:

* When &quot;formula_166&quot;, an &quot;formula_5&quot;-connection simplifies to a linear map &quot;formula_193&quot; and the flatness condition makes it into a Lie algebra morphism, therefore we recover the standard notion of representation of a Lie algebra.
* When &quot;formula_194&quot; and &quot;formula_195&quot; is a representation the Lie algebra formula_75, the trivial vector bundle &quot;formula_197&quot; is automatically a representation of &quot;formula_5&quot;
* Representations of the tangent algebroid &quot;formula_199&quot; are vector bundles endowed with flat connections
* Every Lie algebroid &quot;formula_22&quot; has a natural representation on the line bundle &quot;formula_201&quot;, i.e. the tensor product between the determinant line bundles of &quot;formula_5 &quot;and of formula_149. One can associate a cohomology class in &quot;formula_204&quot; (see below) known as the modular class of the Lie algebroid. For the cotangent algebroid &quot;formula_205&quot; associated to a Poisson manifold &quot;formula_97&quot; one recovers the modular class of &quot;formula_151&quot;.

Note that there an arbitrary Lie groupoid does not have a canonical representation on its Lie algebroid, playing the role of the adjoint representation of Lie groups on their Lie algebras. However, this becomes possible if one allows the more general notion of representation up to homotopy.

=== Lie algebroid cohomology ===
Consider a Lie algebroid &quot;formula_22&quot; and a representation &quot;formula_187&quot;. Denoting by &quot;formula_210&quot; the space of &quot;formula_211&quot;-differential forms on &quot;formula_5&quot; with values in the vector bundle &quot;formula_91&quot;, one can define a differential &quot;formula_214&quot; with the following Koszul-like formula:formula_215Thanks to the flatness of &quot;formula_178&quot;, &quot;formula_217&quot; becomes a cochain complex and its cohomology, denoted by &quot;formula_218&quot;, is called the Lie algebroid cohomology of &quot;formula_5&quot; with coefficients in the representation &quot;formula_187&quot;.

This general definition recovers well-known cohomology theories:

* The cohomology of a Lie algebroid &quot;formula_221&quot; coincides with the Chevalley-Eilenberg cohomology of &quot;formula_75&quot; as a Lie algebra.
* The cohomology of a tangent Lie algebroid &quot;formula_67&quot; coincides with the de Rham cohomology of &quot;formula_6&quot;.
* The cohomology of a foliation Lie algebroid &quot;formula_225&quot; coincides with the leafwise cohomology of the foliation &quot;formula_72&quot;.
*The cohomology of the cotangent Lie algebroid &quot;formula_149&quot; associated to a Poisson structure &quot;formula_151&quot; coincides with the Poisson cohomology of &quot;formula_151.&quot;

== Lie groupoid-Lie algebroid correspondence ==
The standard construction which associates a Lie algebra to a Lie group generalises to this setting: to every Lie groupoid &quot;formula_230&quot; one can canonically associate a Lie algebroid &quot;formula_231&quot; defined as follows:

* the vector bundle is formula_232, where &quot;formula_233&quot; is the vertical bundle of the source fibre &quot;formula_234&quot; and &quot;formula_235&quot; is the groupoid unit map; 
* the sections of &quot;formula_5&quot; are identified with the right-invariant vector fields on &quot;formula_84&quot;, so that &quot;formula_2&quot; inherits a Lie bracket; 
* the anchor map is the differential formula_239 of the target map &quot;formula_240&quot;.

Of course, a symmetric construction arises when swapping the role of the source and the target maps, and replacing right- with left-invariant vector fields; an isomorphism between the two resulting Lie algebroids will be given by the differential of the inverse map formula_241.

The flow of a section &quot;formula_242&quot; is the 1-parameter bisection formula_243, defined by &quot;formula_244&quot;, where formula_245 is the flow of the corresponding right-invariant vector field &quot;formula_246&quot;. This allows one to defined the analogue of the exponential map for Lie groups as formula_247.

=== Lie functor ===
The mapping &quot;formula_248&quot; sending a Lie groupoid to a Lie algebroid is actually part of a categorical construction. Indeed, any Lie groupoid morphism &quot;formula_249 &quot;can be differentiated to a morphism&quot; formula_250&quot; between the associated Lie algebroids.

This construction defines a functor from the category of Lie groupoids and their morphisms to the category of Lie algebroids and their morphisms, called the Lie functor.

=== Structures and properties induced from groupoids to algebroids ===
Let formula_251 be a Lie groupoid and formula_252 its associated Lie algebroid. Then

* The isotropy algebras &quot;formula_253&quot; are the Lie algebras of the isotropy groups &quot;formula_254&quot;
* The orbits of &quot;formula_84&quot; coincides with the orbits of &quot;formula_5&quot;
* &quot;formula_84&quot; is transitive and &quot;formula_258&quot; is a submersion if and only if &quot;formula_5&quot; is transitive
* an action &quot;formula_260&quot; of &quot;formula_84&quot; on &quot;formula_262&quot; induces an action &quot;formula_263&quot; of &quot;formula_5&quot; (called infinitesimal action), defined by &quot;formula_265&quot;
* a representation of &quot;formula_84&quot; on a vector bundle &quot;formula_88&quot; induces a representation &quot;formula_178&quot; of &quot;formula_5&quot; on &quot;formula_88&quot;, defined by&quot;formula_271&quot;Moreover, there is a morphism of semirings &quot;formula_272&quot;, which becomes an isomorphism if &quot;formula_84&quot; is source-simply connected.
* there is a morphism formula_274, called Van Est morphism, from the differentiable cohomology of &quot;formula_84&quot; with coefficients in some representation on &quot;formula_91&quot; to the cohomology of &quot;formula_5&quot; with coefficients in the induced representation on &quot;formula_91&quot;. Moreover, if the &quot;formula_279&quot;-fibres of &quot;formula_84&quot; are homologically &quot;formula_211&quot;-connected, then &quot;formula_282&quot; is an isomorphism for &quot;formula_283&quot;, and is injective for &quot;formula_284&quot;.

=== Examples ===
* The Lie algebroid of a Lie group formula_285 is the Lie algebra formula_221
* The Lie algebroid of both the pair groupoid formula_287 and the fundamental groupoid formula_288 is the tangent algebroid formula_67 
* The Lie algebroid of the unit groupoid formula_290 is the zero algebroid formula_70
* The Lie algebroid of a Lie group bundle formula_230 is the Lie algebra bundle formula_22
* The Lie algebroid of an action groupoid formula_294 is the action algebroid formula_77
* The Lie algebroid of a gauge groupoid formula_296 is the Atiyah algebroid formula_297
* The Lie algebroid of a general linear groupoid formula_298 is the general linear algebroid formula_299
* The Lie algebroid of both the holonomy groupoid formula_300 and the monodromy groupoid formula_301 is the foliation algebroid formula_225
* The Lie algebroid of a tangent groupoid formula_303 is the tangent algebroid formula_304, for &quot;formula_305&quot;
* The Lie algebroid of a jet groupoid formula_306 is the jet algebroid formula_307, for &quot;formula_305&quot;

