<doc id="310923" wikidata="Q6543824" url="?curid=310923" title="Lie groupoid">
<text>In mathematics, a Lie groupoid is a groupoid where the set formula_1 of objects and the set formula_2 of morphisms are both manifolds, all the category operations (source and target, composition, identity-assigning map and inversion) are smooth, and the source and target operations

:formula_3

are submersions.

A Lie groupoid can thus be thought of as a &quot;many-object generalization&quot; of a Lie group, just as a groupoid is a many-object generalization of a group. Accordingly, while Lie groups provide a natural model for (classical) continuous symmetries, Lie groupoids are often used as model for (and arise from) generalised, point-dependent symmetries. Extending the correspondence between Lie groups and Lie algebras, Lie groupoids are the global counterparts of Lie algebroids.

Lie groupoids were introduced by Charles Ehresmann under the name &quot;differentiable groupoids&quot;.

== Definition and basic concepts ==
A Lie groupoid consists of

* two smooth manifolds formula_4 and formula_5
* two surjective submersions formula_6 (called, respectively, source and target projections)
* a map formula_7 (called multiplication or composition map), where we use the notation formula_8
* a map formula_9 (called unit map or object inclusion map), where we use the notation formula_10
* a map formula_11 (called inversion), where we use the notation formula_12

such that

* the composition satisfies formula_13 and formula_14 for every formula_15 for which the composition is defined
*the composition is associative, i.e. formula_16 for every formula_17 for which the composition is defined
* formula_18 works as an identity, i.e. formula_19 for every formula_20 and formula_21 and formula_22 for every formula_23
* formula_24 works as an inverse, i.e. formula_25 and formula_26 for every formula_23.

Using the language of category theory, a Lie groupoid can be more compactly defined as a groupoid (i.e. a small category where all the morphisms are invertible) such that the sets formula_5 of objects and formula_4 of morphisms are manifolds, the maps formula_30, formula_31, formula_32, formula_33 and formula_34 are smooth and formula_30 and formula_31 are submersions. A Lie groupoid is therefore not simply a groupoid object in the category of smooth manifolds: one has to ask the additional property that formula_30 and formula_31 are submersions.

Lie groupoids are often denoted by formula_39, where the two arrows represent the source and the target. The notation formula_40 is also frequently used, especially when stressing the simplicial structure of the associated nerve.

In order to include more natural examples, the manifold formula_4 is not required in general to be Hausdorff or second countable (while formula_5 and all other spaces are).

=== Alternative definitions ===
The original definition by Ehresmann required formula_4 and formula_5 to possess a smooth structure such that only formula_32 is smooth and the maps formula_46 and formula_47 are subimmersions (i.e. have locally constant rank). Such definition proved to be too weak and was replaced by Pradines with the one currently used.

While some authors introduced weaker definitions which did not require formula_30 and formula_31 to be submersions, these properties are fundamental to develop the entire Lie theory of groupoids and algebroids.

=== First properties ===
The fact that the source and the target map of a Lie groupoid formula_50 are smooth submersions has some immediate consequences:
* the formula_30-fibres formula_52, the formula_31-fibres formula_54, and the set of composable morphisms formula_55 are submanifolds;
* the inversion map formula_33 is a diffeomorphism;
*the unit map formula_34 is a smooth embedding;
*the isotropy groups formula_58 are Lie groups;
* the orbits formula_59 are immersed submanifolds;
* the formula_30-fibre formula_61 at a point formula_20 is a principal formula_58-bundle over the orbit formula_64 at that point.

=== Subobjects and morphisms ===
A Lie subgroupoid of a Lie groupoid formula_50 is a subgroupoid formula_66 (i.e. a subcategory of the category formula_4) with the extra requirement that formula_68 is an immersed submanifold. As for a subcategory, a (Lie) subgroupoid is called wide if formula_69. Any Lie groupoid formula_50 has two canonical wide subgroupoids:

* the unit/identity Lie subgroupoid formula_71;
* the inner subgroupoid formula_72, i.e. the bundle of isotropy groups (which however may fail to be smooth in general).

A normal Lie subgroupoid is a wide Lie subgroupoid formula_68 inside formula_74 such that, for every formula_75 with formula_76, one has formula_77. The isotropy groups of formula_78 are therefore normal subgroups of the isotropy groups of formula_4.

A Lie groupoid morphism between two Lie groupoids formula_50 and formula_66 is a groupoid morphism formula_82 (i.e. a functor between the categories formula_4 and formula_78), where both formula_85 and formula_86 are smooth. The kernel formula_87 of a morphism between Lie groupoids over the same base manifold is automatically a normal Lie subgroupoid.

The quotient formula_88 has a natural groupoid structure such that the projection formula_89 is a groupoid morphism; however, unlike quotients of Lie groups, formula_90 may fail to be a Lie groupoid in general. Accordingly, the isomorphism theorems for groupoids cannot be specialised to the entire category of Lie groupoids, but only to special classes.

A Lie groupoid is called abelian if its isotropy Lie groups are abelian. For similar reasons as above, while the definition of abelianisation of a group extends to set-theoretical groupoids, in the Lie case the analogue of the quotient formula_91 may not exist or be smooth.

=== Bisections ===
A bisection of a Lie groupoid formula_50 is a smooth map formula_93 such that formula_94 and formula_95 is a diffeomorphism of formula_5. In order to overcome the lack of symmetry between the source and the target, a bisection can be equivalently defined as a submanifold formula_97 such that formula_98 and formula_99 are diffeomorphisms; the relation between the two definitions is given by formula_100.

The set of bisections forms a group, with the multiplication formula_101 defined asformula_102and inversion defined asformula_103Note that the definition is given in such a way that, if formula_104 and formula_105, then formula_106 and formula_107.

The group of bisections can be given the compact-open topology, as well as an (infinite-dimensional) structure of Fréchet manifold compatible with the group structure, making it into a Fréchet-Lie group.

A local bisection formula_108 is defined analogously, but the multiplication between local bisections is of course only partially defined.

==Examples==

=== Trivial and extreme cases ===
*Lie groupoids formula_109 with one object are the same thing as Lie groups.
*Given any manifold formula_5, there is a Lie groupoid formula_111 called the pair groupoid, with precisely one morphism from any object to any other.
*The two previous examples are particular cases of the trivial groupoid formula_112, with structure maps formula_113, formula_114, formula_115, formula_116 and formula_117. 
*Given any manifold formula_5, there is a Lie groupoid formula_119 called the unit groupoid, with precisely one morphism from one object to itself, namely the identity, and no morphisms between different objects.
*More generally, Lie groupoids with formula_120 are the same thing as bundle of Lie groups (not necessarily locally trivial). For instance, any vector bundle is a bundle of abelian groups, so it is in particular a(n abelian) Lie groupoid.

=== Constructions from other Lie groupoids ===
*Given any Lie groupoid formula_50 and a surjective submersion formula_122, there is a Lie groupoid formula_123, called its pullback groupoid or induced groupoid, where formula_124 contains triples formula_125 such that formula_126 and formula_127, and the multiplication is defined using the multiplication of formula_4. For instance, the pullback of the pair groupoid of formula_5 is the pair groupoid of formula_130.
*Given any two Lie groupoids formula_131 and formula_132, there is a Lie groupoid formula_133, called their direct product, such that the groupoid morphisms formula_134 and formula_135 are surjective submersions.
*Given any Lie groupoid formula_50, there is a Lie groupoid formula_137, called its tangent groupoid, obtained by considering the tangent bundle of formula_4 and formula_5 and the differential of the structure maps.
*Given any Lie groupoid formula_50, there is a Lie groupoid formula_141, called its cotangent groupoid obtained by considering the cotangent bundle of formula_4, the dual of the Lie algebroid formula_143 (see below), and suitable structure maps involving the differentials of the left and right translations.
*Given any Lie groupoid formula_50, there is a Lie groupoid formula_145, called its jet groupoid, obtained by considering the k-jets of the local bisections of formula_4 (with smooth structure inherited from the jet bundle of formula_147) and setting formula_148, formula_149, formula_150, formula_151 and formula_152.

=== Examples from differential geometry ===
*Given a submersion formula_153, there is a Lie groupoid formula_154, called the submersion groupoid or fibred pair groupoid, whose structure maps are induced from the pair groupoid formula_111 (the condition that formula_156 is a submersion ensures the smoothness of formula_157). If formula_130 is a point, one recovers the pair groupoid.
*Given a Lie group formula_4 acting on a manifold formula_5, there is a Lie groupoid formula_161, called the action groupoid or translation groupoid, with one morphism for each triple formula_162 with formula_163.
*Given any vector bundle formula_164, there is a Lie groupoid formula_165, called the general linear groupoid, with morphisms between formula_166 being linear isomorphisms between the fibres formula_167 and formula_168. For instance, if formula_169 is the trivial vector bundle of rank formula_170, then formula_165 is the action groupoid.
*Any principal bundle formula_172 with structure group &quot;formula_4&quot; defines a Lie groupoid formula_174, where &quot;formula_4&quot; acts on the pairs formula_176 componentwise, called the gauge groupoid. The multiplication is defined via compatible representatives as in the pair groupoid.
*Any foliation formula_177 on a manifold formula_5 defines two Lie groupoids, formula_179 (or formula_180) and formula_181, called respectively the monodromy/homotopy/fundamental groupoid and the holonomy groupoid of formula_177, whose morphisms consist of the homotopy, respectively holonomy, equivalence classes of paths entirely lying in a leaf of formula_177. For instance, when formula_177 is the trivial foliation with only one leaf, one recovers, respectively, the fundamental groupoid and the pair groupoid of formula_5. On the other hand, when formula_177 is a simple foliation, i.e. the foliation by (connected) fibres of a submersion formula_153, its holonomy groupoid is precisely the submersion groupoid formula_157 but its monodromy groupoid may even fail to be Hausdorff, due to a general criterion in terms of vanishing cycles. In general, many elementary foliations give rise to monodromy and holonomy groupoids which are not Hausdorff.
*Given any pseudogroup formula_189, there is a Lie groupoid formula_190, called its germ groupoid, endowed with the sheaf topology and with structure maps analogous to those of the jet groupoid. This is another natural example of Lie groupoid whose arrow space is not Hausdorff nor second countable.

== Important classes of Lie groupoids ==
Note that some of the following classes make sense already in the category of set-theoretical or topological groupoids.

=== Transitive groupoids ===
A Lie groupoid is transitive (in older literature also called connected) if it satisfies one of the following equivalent conditions:

* there is only one orbit;
* there is at least a morphism between any two objects;
* the map formula_191 (also known as the anchor of formula_50) is surjective.

Gauge groupoids constitute the prototypical examples of transitive Lie groupoids: indeed, any transitive Lie groupoid is isomorphic to the gauge groupoid of some principal bundle, namely the formula_58-bundle formula_194, for any point formula_20. For instance:

* the trivial Lie groupoid formula_112 is transitive and arise from the trivial principal formula_4-bundle formula_198. As particular cases, Lie groups formula_109 and pair groupoids formula_111 are trivially transitive, and arise, respectively, from the principal formula_4-bundle formula_202, and from the principal formula_203-bundle formula_204;
* an action groupoid formula_161 is transitive if and only if the group action is transitive, and in such case it arises from the principal bundle formula_206 with structure group the isotropy group (at an arbitrary point);
* the general linear groupoid of formula_207 is transitive, and arises from the frame bundle formula_208;
*pullback groupoids, jet groupoids and tangent groupoids of formula_50 are transitive if and only if formula_50 is transitive.

As a less trivial instance of the correspondence between transitive Lie groupoids and principal bundles, consider the fundamental groupoid formula_211 of a (connected) smooth manifold formula_5. This is naturally a topological groupoid, which is moreover transitive; one can see that formula_211 is isomorphic to the gauge groupoid of the universal cover of formula_5. Accordingly, formula_211 inherits a smooth structure which makes it into a Lie groupoid.

Submersions groupoids formula_216 are an example of non-transitive Lie groupoids, whose orbits are precisely the fibres of formula_156.

A stronger notion of transitivity requires the anchor formula_191 to be a surjective submersion. Such condition is also called local triviality, because formula_4 becomes locally isomorphic (as Lie groupoid) to a trivial groupoid over any open formula_220 (as a consequence of the local triviality of principal bundles).

When the space formula_4 is second countable, transitivity implies local triviality. Accordingly, these two conditions are equivalent for many examples but not for all of them: for instance, if formula_222 is a transitive pseudogroup, its germ groupoid formula_223 is transitive but not locally trivial.

=== Proper groupoids ===
A Lie groupoid is called proper if formula_191 is a proper map. As a consequence

* all isotropy groups of formula_4 are compact;
* all orbits of formula_4 are closed submanifolds;
* the orbit space formula_227 is Hausdorff.

For instance:

* a Lie group is proper if and only if it is compact;
* pair groupoids are always proper;
*unit groupoids are always proper;
* an action groupoid is proper if and only if the action is proper;
*the fundamental groupoid is proper if and only if the fundamental groups are finite.
As seen above, properness for Lie groupoids is the &quot;right&quot; analogue of compactness for Lie groups. One could also consider more &quot;natural&quot; conditions, e.g. asking that the source map formula_147 is proper (then formula_50 is called s-proper), or that the entire space formula_4 is compact (then formula_50 is called compact), but these requirements turns out to be too strict for many examples and applications.

=== Étale groupoids ===
A Lie groupoid is called étale if it satisfies one of the following equivalent conditions:

* the dimensions of formula_4 and formula_5 are equal;
* formula_30 is a local diffeomorphism;
* all the formula_30-fibres are discrete

As a consequence, also the formula_31-fibres, the isotropy groups and the orbits become discrete.

For instance:

* a Lie group is étale if and only if it is discrete;
*pair groupoids are never étale;
*unit groupoids are always étale;
*an action groupoid is étale if and only if formula_4 is discrete;
* germ groupoids of pseudogroups are always étale.

=== Effective groupoids ===
An étale groupoid is called effective if, for any two local bisections formula_238, the condition formula_239 implies formula_240. For instance:

* Lie groups are effective if and only if are trivial;
*unit groupoids are always effective;
*an action groupoid is effective if the formula_4-action is free and formula_4 is discrete.
In general, any effective étale groupoid arise as the germ groupoid of some pseudogroup. However, a (more involved) definition of effectiveness, which does not assume the étale property, can also be given.

=== Source-connected groupoids ===
A Lie groupoid is called formula_30-connected if all its formula_30-fibres are connected. Similarly, one talks about formula_30-simply connected groupoids (when the formula_30-fibres are simply connected) or source-k-connected groupoids (when the formula_30-fibres are k-connected, i.e. the first formula_170 homotopy groups are trivial).

Note that the entire space of arrows formula_4 is not asked to satisfy any connectedness hypothesis. However, if formula_4 is a source-formula_170-connected Lie groupoid over a formula_170-connected manifold, then formula_4 itself is automatically formula_170-connected.

For instanceː

* Lie groups are source formula_170-connected if and only if they are formula_170-connected;
* a pair groupoid is source formula_170-connected if and only if formula_5 is formula_170-connected;
* unit groupoids are always source formula_170-connected;
* action groupoids are source formula_170-connected if and only if formula_4 is formula_170-connected;
* monodromy groupoids (hence also fundamental groupoids) are source simply connected;
* a gauge groupoid associated to a principal bundle formula_172 is source formula_170-connected if and only if the total space formula_266 is.

== Further related concepts ==
=== Actions and principal bundles ===
Recall that an action of a groupoid formula_50 on a set formula_266 along a function formula_269 is defined via a collection of maps formula_270 for each morphism formula_23 between formula_166. Accordingly, an action of a Lie groupoid formula_50 on a manifold formula_266 along a smooth map formula_269 consists of a groupoid action where the maps formula_276 are smooth. Of course, for every formula_20 there is an induced smooth action of the isotropy group formula_58 on the fibre formula_279.

Given a Lie groupoid formula_50, a principal formula_4-bundle consists of a formula_4-space formula_266 and a formula_4-invariant surjective submersion formula_285 such thatformula_286is a diffeomorphism. Equivalent (but more involved) definitions can be given using formula_4-valued cocycles or local trivialisations.

When formula_4 is a Lie groupoid over a point, one recovers, respectively, standard Lie group actions and principal bundles.

=== Representations ===
A representation of a Lie groupoid formula_50 consists of a Lie groupoid action on a vector bundle formula_290, such that the action is fibrewise linear, i.e. each bijection formula_291 is a linear isomorphism. Equivalently, a representation of formula_4 on formula_207 can be described as a Lie groupoid morphism from formula_4 to the general linear groupoid formula_295.

Of course, any fibre formula_167 becomes a representation of the isotropy group formula_58. More generally, representations of transitive Lie groupoids are uniquely determined by representations of their isotropy groups, via the construction of the associated vector bundle.

Examples of Lie groupoids representations include the following:

* representations of Lie groups formula_109 recover standard Lie group representations
* representations of pair groupoids formula_111 are trivial vector bundles
* representations of unit groupoids formula_300 are vector bundles
* representations of action groupoid formula_161 are formula_4-equivariant vector bundles
* representations of fundamental groupoids formula_211 are vector bundles endowed with flat connections

The set formula_304 of isomorphism classes of representations of a Lie groupoid formula_50 has a natural structure of semiring, with direct sums and tensor products of vector bundles.

=== Differentiable cohomology ===
The notion of differentiable cohomology for Lie groups generalises naturally also to Lie groupoids: the definition relies on the simplicial structure of the nerve formula_306 of formula_50, viewed as a category.

More precisely, recall that the space formula_308 consists of strings of formula_309 composable morphisms, i.e.

formula_310

and consider the map formula_311.

A differentiable &quot;formula_309&quot;-cochain of formula_50 with coefficients in some representation formula_314 is a smooth section of the pullback vector bundle formula_315. One denotes by formula_316 the space of such &quot;formula_309&quot;-cochains, and considers the differential formula_318, defined as

formula_319

Then formula_320 becomes a cochain complex and its cohomology, denoted by formula_321, is called the differentiable cohomology of formula_50 with coefficients in formula_314. Note that, since the differential at degree zero is formula_324, one has always formula_325.

Of course, the differentiable cohomology of formula_109 as a Lie groupoid coincides with the standard differentiable cohomology of formula_4 as a Lie group (in particular, for discrete groups one recovers the usual group cohomology). On the other hand, for any &quot;proper&quot; Lie groupoid formula_50, one can prove that formula_329 for every formula_330.

=== The Lie algebroid of a Lie groupoid ===

Any Lie groupoid formula_50 has an associated Lie algebroid formula_332, obtained with a construction similar to the one which associates a Lie algebra to any Lie groupː

* the vector bundle formula_332 is the vertical bundle with respect to the source map, restricted to the elements tangent to the identities, i.e. formula_334;
* the Lie bracket is obtained by identifying formula_335 with the left-invariant vector fields on formula_4, and by transporting their Lie bracket to formula_143;
* the anchor map formula_338 is the differential of the target map formula_339 restricted to formula_143.

The Lie group–Lie algebra correspondence generalises to some extends also to Lie groupoids: the first two Lie&#x27;s theorem (also known as the subgroups–subalgebras theorem and the homomorphisms theorem) can indeed be easily adapted to this setting.

In particular, as in standard Lie theory, for any s-connected Lie groupoid formula_4 there is a unique (up to isomorphism) s-simply connected Lie groupoid formula_342 with the same Lie algebroid of formula_4, and a local diffeomorphism formula_344 which is a groupoid morphism. For instance,

* given any connected manifold formula_5 its pair groupoid formula_346 is s-connected but not s-simply connected, while its fundamental groupoid formula_211 is. They both have the same Lie algebroid, namely the tangent bundle formula_348, and the local diffeomorphism formula_349 is given by formula_350.
* given any foliation formula_177 on formula_5, its holonomy groupoid formula_353 is s-connected but not s-simply connected, while its monodromy groupoid formula_354 is. They both have the same Lie algebroid, namely the foliation algebroid formula_355, and the local diffeomorphism formula_356 is given by formula_357 (since the homotopy classes are smaller than the holonomy ones).

However, there is no analogue of Lie&#x27;s third theoremː while several classes of Lie algebroids are integrable, there are examples of Lie algebroids, for instance related to foliation theory, which do not admit an integrating Lie groupoid. The general obstructions to the existence of such integration depend on the topology of formula_4.

==Morita equivalence==
As discussed above, the standard notion of (iso)morphism of groupoids (viewed as functors between categories) restricts naturally to Lie groupoids. However, there is a more coarse notion of equivalence, called Morita equivalence, which is more flexible and useful in applications.

First, a Morita map (also known as a weak equivalence or essential equivalence) between two Lie groupoids formula_359 and formula_360 consists of a Lie groupoid morphism from G to H which is moreover fully faithful and essentially surjective (adapting these categorical notions to the smooth context). We say that two Lie groupoids formula_361 and formula_360 are Morita equivalent if and only if there exists a third Lie groupoid formula_363 together with two Morita maps from &quot;G&quot; to &quot;K&quot; and from &quot;H&quot; to &quot;K&quot;.

A more explicit description of Morita equivalence (e.g. useful to check that it is an equivalence relation) requires the existence of two surjective submersions formula_364 and formula_365 together with a left formula_4-action and a right formula_78-action, commuting with each other and making formula_266 into a principal bi-bundle.

=== Morita invariance ===
Many properties of Lie groupoids, e.g. being proper, being Hausdorff or being transitive, are Morita invariant. On the other hand, being étale is not Morita invariant.

In addition, a Morita equivalence between formula_361 and formula_360 preserves their &quot;transverse geometry&quot;, i.e. it induces:

* a homeomorphism between the orbit spaces formula_371 and formula_372;
* an isomorphism formula_373 between the isotropy groups at corresponding points formula_374 and formula_375;
* an isomorphism formula_376 between the normal representations of the isotropy groups at corresponding points formula_374 and formula_375.
Last, the differentiable cohomologies of two Morita equivalent Lie groupoids are isomorphic.

=== Examples ===

* Isomorphic Lie groupoids are trivially Morita equivalent.
* Two Lie groups are Morita equivalent if and only if they are isomorphic as Lie groups.
*Two unit groupoids are Morita equivalent if and only if the base manifolds are diffeomorphic.
* Any transitive Lie groupoid is Morita equivalent to its isotropy groups.
* Given a Lie groupoid formula_379 and a surjective submersion formula_380, the pullback groupoid formula_123 is Morita equivalent to formula_379.
* Given a free and proper Lie group action of formula_4 on formula_5 (therefore the quotient formula_227 is a manifold), the action groupoid formula_161 is Morita equivalent to the unit groupoid formula_387.
* A Lie groupoid formula_4 is Morita equivalent to an étale groupoid if and only if all isotropy groups of formula_4 are discrete.

A concrete instance of the last example goes as follows. Let &quot;M&quot; be a smooth manifold and formula_390 an open cover of &quot;formula_5&quot;. Its Čech groupoid formula_361 is defined by the disjoint unions formula_393 and formula_394, where formula_395. The source and target map are defined as the embeddings formula_396 and formula_397, and the multiplication is the obvious one if we read the formula_398 as subsets of &quot;M&quot; (compatible points in formula_398 and formula_400 actually are the same in &quot;formula_5&quot; and also lie in formula_402). The Čech groupoid is in fact the pullback groupoid, under the obvious submersion formula_403&quot;,&quot; of the unit groupoid formula_404. As such, Čech groupoids associated to different open covers of &quot;formula_5&quot; are Morita equivalent.

=== Smooth stacks ===
Investigating the structure of the orbit space of a Lie groupoid leads to the notion of a smooth stack. For instance, the orbit space is a smooth manifold if the isotropy groups are trivial (as in the example of the Čech groupoid), but it is not smooth in general. The solution is to revert the problem and to define a smooth stack as a Morita-equivalence class of Lie groupoids. The natural geometric objects living on the stack are the geometric objects on Lie groupoids invariant under Morita-equivalence: an example is the Lie groupoid cohomology.

Since the notion of smooth stack is quite general, obviously all smooth manifolds are smooth stacks. Other classes of examples include orbifolds, which are (equivalence classes of) proper étale Lie groupoids, and orbit spaces of foliations.

