<doc id="310950" wikidata="Q1365548" url="?curid=310950" title="Principal bundle">
<text>In mathematics, a principal bundle is a mathematical object that formalizes some of the essential features of the Cartesian product formula_1 of a space formula_2 with a group formula_3. In the same way as with the Cartesian product, a principal bundle formula_4 is equipped with
# An action of formula_3 on formula_4, analogous to formula_7 for a product space (where formula_8 is an element of formula_4 and formula_10 is the group element from formula_3; the group action is conventionally a right action).
# A projection onto formula_2. For a product space, this is just the projection onto the first factor, formula_13.
Unless it is the product space formula_1, a principal bundle lacks a preferred choice of identity cross-section; it has no preferred analog of formula_15. Likewise, there is not generally a projection onto formula_3 generalizing the projection onto the second factor, formula_17 that exists for the Cartesian product. They may also have a complicated topology that prevents them from being realized as a product space even if a number of arbitrary choices are made to try to define such a structure by defining it on smaller pieces of the space.

A common example of a principal bundle is the frame bundle formula_18 of a vector bundle formula_19, which consists of all ordered bases of the vector space attached to each point. The group formula_20 in this case, is the general linear group, which acts on the right in the usual way: by changes of basis. Since there is no natural way to choose an ordered basis of a vector space, a frame bundle lacks a canonical choice of identity cross-section.

Principal bundles have important applications in topology and differential geometry and mathematical gauge theory. They have also found application in physics where they form part of the foundational framework of physical gauge theories. 

==Formal definition==

A principal formula_3-bundle, where formula_3 denotes any topological group, is a fiber bundle formula_23 together with a continuous right action formula_24 such that formula_3 preserves the fibers of formula_4 (i.e. if formula_27 then formula_28 for all formula_29) and acts freely and transitively (meaning each fiber is a G-torsor) on them in such a way that for each formula_30 and formula_27, the map formula_32 sending formula_33 to formula_34 is a homeomorphism. In particular each fiber of the bundle is homeomorphic to the group formula_3 itself. Frequently, one requires the base space formula_2 to be Hausdorff and possibly paracompact.

Since the group action preserves the fibers of formula_23 and acts transitively, it follows that the orbits of the formula_3-action are precisely these fibers and the orbit space formula_39 is homeomorphic to the base space formula_2. Because the action is free and transitive, the fibers have the structure of G-torsors. A formula_3-torsor is a space that is homeomorphic to formula_3 but lacks a group structure since there is no preferred choice of an identity element.

An equivalent definition of a principal formula_3-bundle is as a formula_3-bundle formula_23 with fiber formula_3 where the structure group acts on the fiber by left multiplication. Since right multiplication by formula_3 on the fiber commutes with the action of the structure group, there exists an invariant notion of right multiplication by formula_3 on formula_4. The fibers of formula_50 then become right formula_3-torsors for this action.

The definitions above are for arbitrary topological spaces. One can also define principal formula_3-bundles in the category of smooth manifolds. Here formula_23 is required to be a smooth map between smooth manifolds, formula_3 is required to be a Lie group, and the corresponding action on formula_4 should be smooth.

==Examples==

=== Trivial bundle and sections ===
Over an open ball formula_56, or formula_57, with induced coordinates formula_58, any principal formula_3-bundle is isomorphic to a trivial bundleformula_60and a smooth section formula_61 is equivalently given by a (smooth) function formula_62 sinceformula_63for some smooth function. For example, if formula_64, the Lie group of formula_65 unitary matrices, then a section can be constructed by considering four real-valued functionsformula_66and applying them to the parameterization

formula_67This same procedure valids by taking a parameterization of a collection of matrices defining a Lie group formula_3 and by considering the set of functions from a patch of the base space formula_69 to formula_70 and inserting them into the parameterization.

=== Other examples ===

* The prototypical example of a smooth principal bundle is the frame bundle of a smooth manifold formula_71, often denoted formula_72 or formula_73. Here the fiber over a point formula_74 is the set of all frames (i.e. ordered bases) for the tangent space formula_75. The general linear group formula_76 acts freely and transitively on these frames. These fibers can be glued together in a natural way so as to obtain a principal formula_76-bundle over formula_71.
* Variations on the above example include the orthonormal frame bundle of a Riemannian manifold. Here the frames are required to be orthonormal with respect to the metric. The structure group is the orthogonal group formula_79. The example also works for bundles other than the tangent bundle; if formula_19 is any vector bundle of rank formula_81 over formula_71, then the bundle of frames of formula_19 is a principal formula_84-bundle, sometimes denoted formula_18.
* A normal (regular) covering space formula_86 is a principal bundle where the structure group
: formula_87
: acts on the fibres of formula_88 via the monodromy action. In particular, the universal cover of formula_2 is a principal bundle over formula_2 with structure group formula_91 (since the universal cover is simply connected and thus formula_92 is trivial).
* Let formula_3 be a Lie group and let formula_94 be a closed subgroup (not necessarily normal). Then formula_3 is a principal formula_94-bundle over the (left) coset space formula_97. Here the action of formula_94 on formula_3 is just right multiplication. The fibers are the left cosets of formula_94 (in this case there is a distinguished fiber, the one containing the identity, which is naturally isomorphic to formula_94).
* Consider the projection formula_102 given by formula_103. This principal formula_104-bundle is the associated bundle of the Möbius strip. Besides the trivial bundle, this is the only principal formula_104-bundle over formula_106.
* Projective spaces provide some more interesting examples of principal bundles. Recall that the formula_107-sphere formula_108 is a two-fold covering space of real projective space formula_109. The natural action of formula_110 on formula_108 gives it the structure of a principal formula_110-bundle over formula_109. Likewise, formula_114 is a principal formula_115-bundle over complex projective space formula_116 and formula_117 is a principal formula_118-bundle over quaternionic projective space formula_119. We then have a series of principal bundles for each positive formula_107:
: formula_121
: formula_122
: formula_123
: Here formula_124 denotes the unit sphere in formula_125 (equipped with the Euclidean metric). For all of these examples the formula_126 cases give the so-called Hopf bundles.

==Basic properties==

===Trivializations and cross sections===

One of the most important questions regarding any fiber bundle is whether or not it is trivial, &quot;i.e.&quot; isomorphic to a product bundle. For principal bundles there is a convenient characterization of triviality:

:Proposition. &quot;A principal bundle is trivial if and only if it admits a global section.&quot;

The same is not true in general for other fiber bundles. For instance, vector bundles always have a zero section whether they are trivial or not and sphere bundles may admit many global sections without being trivial.

The same fact applies to local trivializations of principal bundles. Let be a principal -bundle. An open set in admits a local trivialization if and only if there exists a local section on . Given a local trivialization

