===Characterization of smooth principal bundles===

If formula_137 is a smooth principal formula_3-bundle then formula_3 acts freely and properly on formula_4 so that the orbit space formula_39 is diffeomorphic to the base space formula_2. It turns out that these properties completely characterize smooth principal bundles. That is, if formula_4 is a smooth manifold, formula_3 a Lie group and formula_145 a smooth, free, and proper right action then
*formula_39 is a smooth manifold,
*the natural projection formula_147 is a smooth submersion, and
*formula_4 is a smooth principal formula_3-bundle over formula_39.

==Use of the notion==

===Reduction of the structure group===

Given a subgroup H of G one may consider the bundle formula_151 whose fibers are homeomorphic to the coset space formula_97. If the new bundle admits a global section, then one says that the section is a reduction of the structure group from formula_3 to formula_94 . The reason for this name is that the (fiberwise) inverse image of the values of this section form a subbundle of formula_4 that is a principal formula_94-bundle. If formula_94 is the identity, then a section of formula_4 itself is a reduction of the structure group to the identity. Reductions of the structure group do not in general exist.

Many topological questions about the structure of a manifold or the structure of bundles over it that are associated to a principal formula_3-bundle may be rephrased as questions about the admissibility of the reduction of the structure group (from formula_3 to formula_94). For example:

* A formula_162-dimensional real manifold admits an almost-complex structure if the frame bundle on the manifold, whose fibers are formula_163, can be reduced to the group formula_164.
* An formula_107-dimensional real manifold admits a formula_81-plane field if the frame bundle can be reduced to the structure group formula_167.
* A manifold is orientable if and only if its frame bundle can be reduced to the special orthogonal group, formula_168.
* A manifold has spin structure if and only if its frame bundle can be further reduced from formula_169 to formula_170 the Spin group, which maps to formula_169 as a double cover.

Also note: an formula_107-dimensional manifold admits formula_107 vector fields that are linearly independent at each point if and only if its frame bundle admits a global section. In this case, the manifold is called parallelizable.

===Associated vector bundles and frames===

If formula_4 is a principal formula_3-bundle and formula_125 is a linear representation of formula_3, then one can construct a vector bundle formula_178 with fibre formula_125, as the quotient of the product formula_4×formula_125 by the diagonal action of formula_3. This is a special case of the associated bundle construction, and formula_19 is called an associated vector bundle to formula_4. If the representation of formula_3 on formula_125 is faithful, so that formula_3 is a subgroup of the general linear group GL(formula_125), then formula_19 is a formula_3-bundle and formula_4 provides a reduction of structure group of the frame bundle of formula_19 from formula_193 to formula_3. This is the sense in which principal bundles provide an abstract formulation of the theory of frame bundles.

==Classification of principal bundles==
Any topological group admits a classifying space : the quotient by the action of of some weakly contractible space, &quot;e.g.&quot;, a topological space with vanishing homotopy groups. The classifying space has the property that any principal bundle over a paracompact manifold &quot;B&quot; is isomorphic to a pullback of the principal bundle . In fact, more is true, as the set of isomorphism classes of principal bundles over the base identifies with the set of homotopy classes of maps .

