<doc id="311017" wikidata="Q7293198" url="?curid=311017" title="Rank-into-rank">
<text>In set theory, a branch of mathematics, a rank-into-rank embedding is a large cardinal property defined by one of the following four axioms given in order of increasing consistency strength. (A set of rank formula_1 is one of the elements of the set formula_2 of the von Neumann hierarchy.)

*Axiom I3: There is a nontrivial elementary embedding of formula_2 into itself.
*Axiom I2: There is a nontrivial elementary embedding of formula_4 into a transitive class formula_5 that includes formula_2 where formula_7 is the first fixed point above the critical point.
*Axiom I1: There is a nontrivial elementary embedding of formula_8 into itself.
*Axiom I0: There is a nontrivial elementary embedding of formula_9 into itself with critical point below formula_7.

These are essentially the strongest known large cardinal axioms not known to be inconsistent in ZFC; the axiom for Reinhardt cardinals is stronger, but is not consistent with the axiom of choice.

If formula_11 is the elementary embedding mentioned in one of these axioms and formula_12 is its critical point, then formula_7 is the limit of formula_14 as formula_15 goes to formula_16. More generally, if the axiom of choice holds, it is provable that if there is a nontrivial elementary embedding of formula_17 into itself then formula_18 is either a limit ordinal of cofinality formula_16 or the successor of such an ordinal.

The axioms I0, I1, I2, and I3 were at first suspected to be inconsistent (in ZFC) as it was thought possible that Kunen&#x27;s inconsistency theorem that Reinhardt cardinals are inconsistent with the axiom of choice could be extended to them, but this has not yet happened and they are now usually believed to be consistent.

Every I0 cardinal formula_12 (speaking here of the critical point of formula_11) is an I1 cardinal.

Every I1 cardinal formula_12 (sometimes called ω-huge cardinals) is an I2 cardinal and has a stationary set of I2 cardinals below it.

Every I2 cardinal formula_12 is an I3 cardinal and has a stationary set of I3 cardinals below it.

Every I3 cardinal formula_12 has another I3 cardinal &quot;above&quot; it and is an formula_15-huge cardinal for every formula_26.

Axiom I1 implies that formula_8 (equivalently, formula_28) does not satisfy V=HOD. There is no set formula_29 definable in formula_8 (even from parameters formula_2 and ordinals formula_32) with formula_33 cofinal in formula_7 and formula_35, that is, no such formula_33 witnesses that formula_7 is singular. And similarly for Axiom I0 and ordinal definability in formula_9 (even from parameters in formula_2). However globally, and even in formula_2, V=HOD is relatively consistent with Axiom I1.

Notice that I0 is sometimes strengthened further by adding an &quot;Icarus set&quot;, so that it would be
*Axiom Icarus set: There is a nontrivial elementary embedding of formula_41 into itself with the critical point below formula_7.
The Icarus set should be in formula_43 but chosen to avoid creating an inconsistency. So for example, it cannot encode a well-ordering of formula_8. See section 10 of Dimonte for more details.

Woodin defined a sequence of sets formula_45 for use as Icarus sets.

